\begin_layout Standard
To begin, we will simply assume that there are 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 positions which have associated with them exogenously given values 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}>x_{2}>\cdots>x_{K}>0$
\end_inset

.
 The idea is that the slot in the first position is the one that consumers
 are most likely to click.
 There are two reasons for this.
 The first is simply that it is closest to the cursor which has just clicked
 the search box in the top right corner of the browser.
 A more compelling argument is a sort of self fullfilling prophecy that
 we will explain in more detail later.
 If consumers think that the most useful ads are in the first position,
 then firms will bid more aggressively for that position.
 However, the firms that are most likely to win the auction for that position
 are the ones who are most likely to make a sale.
 So at least when consumers want to buy, their expectation that the firms
 from whom they are most likely to buy will be in the first position are
 going to be correct.
 Interpret the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}$
\end_inset

 as the expected number of clicks at position 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are 
\begin_inset Formula $m>K$
\end_inset

 firms bidding for the various positions on the web page.
 Firm 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 has characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 that describes its profit per click.
 For simplicity, assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}\ge v_{2}\ge\ldots\ge v_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 The expected revenue of a firm who successfully places their ad in position
 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}x_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Every firm wants the first position, but not all firms will be willing
 to pay the same amount for it.
 All firms, on the other hand, still earn profits by placing their ads in
 lower positions on the web page.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The position auction works as follows: each firm places a bid 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Lets order the bids so that 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1}$
\end_inset

 is the highest bid, 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{2}$
\end_inset

 the second highest, and so on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first and most desirable position is awarded to the bidder who submits
 the highest bid 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 He or she then pays the second highest bid 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{2}$
\end_inset

 for each click.
 Similarly, the bidder who submits the 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{th}$
\end_inset

 highest bid wins the 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{th}$
\end_inset

 position, and then pays the 
\begin_inset Formula $k+1^{st}$
\end_inset

 highest bid for each click he receives.
 Let the bids be ordered from highest to lowest.
 If firm 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 wins the 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{th}$
\end_inset

 best position (with a bid 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}$
\end_inset

) and pays 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k+1}$
\end_inset

, then his or her revenue per click is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(v_{i}-b_{k+1}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that the firm that wins the 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{th}$
\end_inset

 position (i.e., the lowest or worst position) pays the highest bid of among
 bidders who did not win a slot.
 Given some array 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1},\ldots,b_{m}$
\end_inset

 of bids, bidder 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's total payoff when he wins the 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{th}$
\end_inset

 slot is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(v_{i}-b_{k+1}\right)x_{k},
\]

\end_inset

while his payoff is zero if he doesn't win a slot.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As for any problem in which we want to use Nash equilibrium to predict the
 outcome, we need to specify the entire game.
 In other words, we have to describe the payoff a player earns for any array
 of bids, and for any bid that he might submit instead.
 This is a little complex here because we have to figure out what will happen
 when there are ties.
 The first complication we have to deal with is that we can't simply order
 the bids 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1}>b_{2}$
\end_inset

 etc, we need to tie a bid to a bidder.
 The reason for this complication is that we want to allow a bidder 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 to consider submitting bids that are higher than all the others, higher
 than all but one of the others, lower than all the others, etc.
 The rank of a bidder 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's bid is something we are going to determine as part of our equilibrium.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The strategies of the players are just their bids.
 So lets make the switch and imagine that the player whose name is 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 submits a bid 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The rank that this bid has depends on the bids of the other bidders.
 So lets write the bids submitted by all the players as 
\begin_inset Formula $b=\left\{ b^{1},\ldots,b^{m}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 So lets write 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}\left(b\right)$
\end_inset

 to mean the 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{th}$
\end_inset

 highest bid in the array of bids 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1}\left(b\right)$
\end_inset

 is the highest bid submitted by any player, 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{2}\left(b\right)$
\end_inset

 is the second highest bid in the array 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, and so on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We could also write the bids 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 in a slightly different way.
 For example, we could write 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{-i}$
\end_inset

 to mean the array of bids sumitted by the players other than 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}\left(b^{-i}\right)$
\end_inset

 represents the 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{th}$
\end_inset

 highest bid of the bidders 
\emph on
other 
\emph default
than bidder 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Also notice that the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(b^{i},b^{-i}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the same vector as 
\begin_inset Formula $b=\left(b^{1},\ldots,b^{i-1},b^{i},\ldots,b^{m}\right)$
\end_inset

 except that the elements have been re-ordered.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}\left(b\right)=b_{k}\left(b^{i},b^{-i}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we can write the payoff to each player for every array of bids in a
 position auction where the 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{th}$
\end_inset

 position is awarded to the 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{th}$
\end_inset

 highest bidder who is then charged the 
\begin_inset Formula $k+1^{st}$
\end_inset

 highest bid for each click.
 I'll take a shortcut here to make the formula somewhat simpler.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pi^{i}\left(b^{\prime},b^{-i}\right)=\begin{cases}
\left(v_{i}-b_{1}\left(b^{-i}\right)\right)x_{1} & b^{\prime}>b_{1}\left(b^{-i}\right)\\
\left(v_{i}-b_{k+1}\left(b^{-i}\right)\right)x_{k+1} & \exists k<K:b_{k}\left(b^{-i}\right)>b^{\prime}>b_{k+1}\left(b^{-i}\right)\\
0 & \mbox{otherwise.}
\end{cases}\label{profit-function}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a complicated expression, so well go over it.
 When a bidder considers a bid 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, she first checks the bids of the other players (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{-i}$
\end_inset

) and puts them in order 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b_{1}\left(b^{-i}\right),\ldots,b_{m}\left(b^{-i}\right)\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 She then looks to see if her bid 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 is higher than one of the 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 highest bids that the others have submitted.
 For example, if there are four bidders (as there will be in the graphical
 illustration below), and they submit the bids 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 2,4,3,6\right\} $
\end_inset

 (where 2 is submitted by the bidder with identity 1, 4 by bidder with identity
 2, etc, then bidder 3 first takes the other bids 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 2,4,6\right\} $
\end_inset

 and puts them in descending order.
 This gives her the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1}\left(\left\{ 2,4,6\right\} \right)=6$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{2}\left(\left\{ 2,4,6\right\} \right)=4$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{3}\left(\left\{ 2,4,6\right\} \right)=2$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose there are K=3 positions to be won in the auction.
 She sees that there is a value for 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 , i.e., 2, which is less than the number of positions up for auction, ie,
 3, and such that her bid is still at least as large as 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{3}\left(\left\{ 2,4,6\right\} \right)=2$
\end_inset

 .
 That means she will win a slot with this bid, that is slot 
\begin_inset Formula $j+1$
\end_inset

 or 3, and pay 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{3}\left(\left\{ 2,4,6\right\} \right)=2$
\end_inset

 for it.
 Her profit is then the difference between her value and the price 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 multiplied by the average number of clicks associated with slot 3.
 The math expression above is certainly a more consise way of saying this.
 It even works when there are more bidders than slots once you think it
 through.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now you might have noticed already what the shortcut is - I left out the
 possibility of equality.
 The reason I did this (apart from avoiding writing out a long formula)
 is that I already know that placing a bid exactly equal to the bid of another
 player is a weakly dominated strategy.
 It might not matter if the bid doesn't win a slot, but if it does, then
 the slot I get would be randomly decided in a lottery with the bidder with
 whom I had tied.
 If I raise the bid ever so slightly, I would be sure to get the highest
 of the two slots, which is better.
 So I couldn't possibly have an equilibrium is which two bidders submit
 the same bid and one of them actually wins a slot.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that we have the profit function (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "profit-function"

\end_inset

), we basically know the payoffs that each player will get for every array
 of bids.
 That is like knowing what payoffs we put in each cell of the matrix in
 a bimatrix game.
 A Nash equilibrium of this game is an array of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 bids such that no player can improve his payoff given the bids of the other
 players.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can't really do the gambit thing and check every profile of bids for
 profitable deviations.
 There is a continuum of profiles to worry about.
 Solving games like this usually means making a good guess about what the
 equilibrium looks like, then trying to verify your guess is an equilibrium.
 The educated guess here comes from the observation that if you win a slot
 at all, you won't pay what you bid.
 Instead, you'll pay what one of the other players bid.
 So your only real choice is to decide which slot, if any, you want.
 The others' bids completely determine what you pay when you win it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second part of the guess comes from the intution that it is likely to
 be the case that the bidder with the highest value will want the best slot,
 the bidder with the second highest value will want the second best slot,
 and so on.
 Why? Well, at this stage in your reasoning you can't really articulate
 why, but is just seems right.
 Nash equilibrium is going to give us a conceptual tool that will make it
 crystal clear why that intution will work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
WIth that start, lets just guess that each slot with have a price, say 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}\ge p_{2}\ldots\ge p_{K}$
\end_inset

, and that the bidder with the highest value will have to win the best slot,
 and so on as we described above.
 Since bidders are really only choosing which slot to win, this will only
 work if the set of prices satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
v_{i}-p_{i}\ge0\label{non-negative}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\ldots,K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}-p_{K}\le0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i>K$
\end_inset

.
 If this weren't true, then some of the winners would be sorry to have won.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also, since players can also win other players' slots by outbidding them
 (and they don't have to worry about their actual bid), then for 
\begin_inset Formula $K\ge i\ge1$
\end_inset

, player 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

